{
  "doc_id": "45465",
  "text": "Metastatic epidural spinal cord compression (MESCC) is a potentially debilitating and common complication of cancer with an incidence varying between 2.5 and 14% of all cancer patients [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The most common primary solid tumour sites are breast, prostate, lung and myeloma. Survival after MESCC is related to primary tumour type ranging from 17 to 20 months for breast, prostate and myeloma to only 4 months for lung [CITATION_3] . Most cases develop in patients already known to have cancer. Untreated, the majority of patients with spinal cord compression become paraplegic. Early detection and treatment when the patient is still able to walk results in the highest chance of ambulation [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
